    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-06-22T16:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-06-22T16:15:00-05:00" n="275"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d275">
                <head>275. Circular Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Cuba</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d275fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 811.235/6–2255. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MJH1"
                            >Mulliken</persName> and approved by <persName corresp="#p_CEG1"
                            >Cale</persName>. Also sent to Ciudad Trujillo, Port-au-Prince, Mexico
                        City, Panama City, and Lima.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-06-22T16:15:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 22, 1955—4:15 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>737. Administration position revision sugar act announced hearings House
                    Agriculture Committee June 22.<note n="2" xml:id="d275fn2">On June 22 <persName
                            corresp="#p_HHF1">Holland</persName> presented the recommendations of
                        the administration concerning sugar legislation to this committee. His
                        statement and the Department of State’s report to the committee dated June
                        22, signed by Thruston B. Morton, Assistant Secretary of State for
                        Congressional Relations, are printed in <hi rend="italic"
                        >Hearings</hi>–1955, pp. 11–17. Cooley introduced <gloss target="#t_HR1"
                            >H.R.</gloss> 7030 for the executive branch on June 27.</note>
                    Recommendations: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>No change 1955 quotas.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Beginning Jan. 1956 domestic areas would receive 55% increases in
                            consumption above 8,350,000 tons.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Cuban participation share foreign suppliers other than Philippines to
                            remain 96 per cent through 1956.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Beginning Jan. 1957, Cuban share of increases consumption above
                            8,350,000 tons would become 60%; full duty countries’ share 40%. No
                            change Philippine quota.</item>
                        <pb facs="0854" n="820" xml:id="pg_820"/>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Beginning Jan. 1957, 12,000–14,000 tons full duty country quota would
                            go small countries which fill quotas regularly. Remainder be divided
                            regular suppliers this group basis U.S. imports from them
                            1951–1954.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Hoover</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
